An Act concerning a right of publicity.
Be it enacted by the Senate and House of Representatives in General Court assembled, and by the authority
of the same, as follows:
1 Section 1. Definitions
2 As used in this act and sections 2 through 8, inclusive:
3 "Name" refers to the actual or assumed name of a living or deceased individual used to
4 identify that individual.
5 "Persona" means the name, voice, distinctive mannerisms and gestures, signature,
6 photograph, or likeness of an individual, or any element thereof.
7 "Right of publicity" means the property right in an individual's persona for a commercial
8 or fundraising purpose.
9 Section 2. Right of Publicity
10 Each individual shall have a right of publicity in their persona, which shall be freely
11 transferable, assignable, and licensable by means of inter vivos or testamentary transfer,
1 of 4

12 including by will, trust, contract, or other permissible mechanisms. This right shall survive the
13 individual’s death and shall apply regardless of whether the right was exploited during the
14 individual's lifetime.
15 Section 3. Unauthorized Use Prohibited
16 No person may use any aspect of an individual’s right of publicity for the following
17 purposes without prior written consent of the individual or their authorized representative during
18 their lifetime or for seventy years after their death:
19 For commercial purposes, including product or service advertising.
20 For fundraising or soliciting donations.
21 To digitally or otherwise alter the individual’s persona in a manner that:
22 Causes the individual to appear to say or do things they did not consent to, or
23 Places the individual in a false context or situation.
24 Unauthorized use constitutes infringement, regardless of whether the use is for profit or
25 nonprofit purposes.
26 Section 4. Civil Actions
27 (a) The following parties may bring a civil action for violations of this act:
28 Owners of the right of publicity.
29 Licensees with express written authorization.
30 Transferees of the right of publicity.
2 of 4

31 (b) Before initiating an action, partial owners must notify others with ownership interests
32 and provide an opportunity to object. Notification may be delivered by mail or published in a
33 newspaper with general circulation in the municipality where the individual resides or, for
34 deceased individuals, where their estate was probated.
35 (c) An objection must be filed within 20 days of mailed notice or 60 days of published
36 notice. If no objection is made, the right to object is waived.
37 (d) Civil actions are prohibited if parties collectively owning more than 50% of the right
38 of publicity object.
39 (e) Partial owners initiating an action must account for recoveries to other interest
40 holders, less reasonable attorney’s fees and costs.
41 Section 5. Remedies and Damages
42 (a) Massachusetts Superior Courts may issue injunctive relief, including temporary
43 restraining orders and permanent injunctions.
44 (b) Violators are liable for the greater of $2,000 or actual damages, plus any profits
45 directly attributable to the infringement. Statutory damages may consider a single act of
46 infringement as one violation, regardless of the number of reproductions or distributions.
47 (c) Courts may impound materials made or used in violation of this act and order their
48 destruction upon final judgment.
49 (d) Courts may award prevailing parties reasonable attorney’s fees and litigation costs.
50 Section 6. Exceptions
3 of 4

51 The following uses are exempt from this act:
52 Bona fide news or public affairs reporting.
53 Portrayals of public officials or political candidates, unless for commercial purposes
54 without consent.
55 Reporting of public interest events or topics.
56 Original works of fine art.
57 Literary works, theatrical works, and similar creative expressions, unless electronically or
58 digitally altered to distort consent.
59 Truthful identification of authors or performers.
60 Promotional material for exempt works under this section.
61 Section 7. Jurisdiction
62 This act applies to all acts occurring in the Commonwealth of Massachusetts, regardless
63 of the individual’s domicile, residence, or citizenship.
64 Section 8. Additional Rights
65 The rights and remedies provided by this act are cumulative and do not preempt other
66 rights or remedies available under Massachusetts law.
67 Section 9.
68 This bill shall take effect upon passage
